## Pipeline Operator

The `|>` operator chains transformations. Each step receives the output of the previous:

```
GET /api/data
  |> jq: `{ id: (.params.id | tonumber) }`
  |> pg([.id]): `SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = $1`
  |> jq: `.data.rows[0]`
  |> handlebars: `<h1>{{name}}</h1>`
```

The output of each step is merged into the current state except:
 - if the output is not an object, it replaces the current state.
 - for the last step, which replaces the current state.

## Variables

Variables let you name reusable middleware snippets and reference them later with the same middleware.

```
jq weatherData = `{
  "latitude": 30.27,
  "longitude": -97.74,
  "temperature": 38.0
}`

pg teamsQuery = `SELECT * FROM teams`

GET /weather
  |> jq: weatherData

GET /teams
  |> pg: teamsQuery
```

Syntax:
```
<middleware> <name> = `<code>`
```

## Built-in Middleware

### jq — JSON transformation
```
|> jq: `{ result: .data, count: (.items | length) }`
```

### handlebars — Template rendering
```
|> handlebars: `<h1>Hello {{name}}</h1>`
|> handlebars: `{{#each items}}<li>{{this.title}}</li>{{/each}}`
```

Partials can be defined as variables and referenced with `{{>partialName}}`:
```
handlebars cardPartial = `
  <div class="card">
    <h3>{{title}}</h3>
    <p>{{description}}</p>
  </div>
`

GET /page
  |> jq: `{ title: "Hello", description: "World" }`
  |> handlebars: `{{>cardPartial}}`
```

### pg — PostgreSQL queries
```
|> pg: `SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = $1`
|> pg([.id]): `SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = $1`
|> pg([.firstName, .lastName]): `INSERT INTO users (first_name, last_name) VALUES ($1, $2) RETURNING *`
```
Parameters via inline `pg([expr, ...])` or `.sqlParams` array. Returns `{ rows: [...], rowCount: N }`.

Use `!raw` prefix for raw SQL (bypasses parameter escaping — use only with safe, computed values):
```
|> pg([(.keys | map(tostring) | join(","))]): `!raw
  SELECT * FROM employees WHERE team_id::text = ANY(string_to_array($1, ','))
`
```

### fetch — HTTP requests
```
# Simple GET
|> fetch: `https://api.example.com/data`

# Dynamic URL
|> fetch("https://api.example.com/users/" + (.params.id | tostring))

# POST with options
|> fetch(
    "https://api.example.com/users",
    {
      method: "POST",
      headers: { "Content-Type": "application/json" },
      body: { name: .name, email: .email }
    }
  )
```

### Cookies — Setting response cookies
```
|> jq: `{
  message: "Response with cookies",
  setCookies: [
    "sessionId=abc123; HttpOnly; Secure; Max-Age=3600",
    "userId=john; Max-Age=86400",
    "theme=dark; Path=/"
  ]
}`
```
Set `setCookies` to an array of Set-Cookie header strings. The server applies them to the HTTP response automatically.

### Response headers — setHeaders, setCookies
These fields in middleware output are actually applied to the HTTP response:

```
|> jq: `{
  setHeaders: {
    "Location": "/users/123",
    "X-Request-ID": (.headers["x-request-id"] // "generated")
  },
  setCookies: [
    "sessionId=abc123; HttpOnly; Secure; Max-Age=3600"
  ],
  data: {
    id: 123,
    created: true
  }
}`
```

- `setHeaders` adds or overrides response headers.
- `setCookies` adds `Set-Cookie` headers.
- Plain `status` and `contentType` fields are not interpreted by the runtime. They stay in the JSON payload unless your own pipeline reads them.

To set an actual HTTP status, use `result` branch codes:
```
POST /users
  |> pg([.body.name]): `INSERT INTO users (name) VALUES ($1) RETURNING id`
  |> result
    ok(201):
      |> jq: `{
        id: .data.rows[0].id,
        created: true,
        setHeaders: {
          "Location": ("/users/" + (.data.rows[0].id | tostring))
        }
      }`
```

To set a non-200 status from your own logic, create an error and branch on it:
```
GET /users/:id
  |> pg([.params.id]): `SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = $1`
  |> jq: `
    if .data.rowCount == 0 then
      { errors: [{ type: "notFound", message: "User not found" }] }
    else
      .data.rows[0]
    end
  `
  |> result
    ok(200):
      |> jq: `.`
    notFound(404):
      |> jq: `{ error: .errors[0].message }`
```

Actual response content type comes from middleware output metadata, not a `contentType` field in JSON:

- `handlebars` sets `text/html`
- `gg` sets `image/svg+xml` or `image/png`
- Cached responses preserve the cached content type

`setHeaders: { "Content-Type": ... }` can change the header string, but it does not change how WebPipe serializes the body.

### lua — Lua 5.4 scripting
```
|> lua: `
  local id = request.params.id
  return { id = id }
`
```
Helpers available in scripts: `request`, `context`, `getEnv(name)`, `requireScript(name)`, `executeSql(query, params)`, `getFlag(name)`, `setFlag(name, bool)`, `getWhen(name)`, `setWhen(name, bool)`.

### js — JavaScript (Boa engine)
```
|> js: `
  const userId = request.params.id;
  return { userId };
`
```
Same script helpers as lua: `request`, `context`, `getEnv(name)`, `requireScript(name)`, `executeSql(query, params)`, `getFlag(name)`, `setFlag(name, bool)`, `getWhen(name)`, `setWhen(name, bool)`.

### auth — Authentication
```
|> auth: "login"
|> auth: "logout"
|> auth: "register"
|> auth: "required"
|> auth: "optional"
|> auth: "type:admin"
```

### validate — Input validation
```
|> validate: `
  email: email
  name: string(3..50)
  password: string(8..100)
`
```

### cache — Response caching
```
|> cache: `
  ttl: 300
  enabled: true
  keyTemplate: user-{params.id}
`
```

### log — Logging
```
|> log: `level: debug, includeBody: true, includeHeaders: true`
```

### debug — Print state (read-only)
```
|> debug: `optional label`
```

### rateLimit — Rate limiting
```
|> rateLimit: `
  keyTemplate: ip-{ip}-route-{method}-{path}
  limit: 100
  window: 60s
`
```

### Parallel execution with @async and join
```
|> fetch: `https://api/users` @async(users)
|> fetch: `https://api/posts` @async(posts)
|> join: `users,posts`
```
Results available at `.async.users` and `.async.posts`.

### gg — Chart generation (gramgraph)
```
|> gg({ "type": "svg", "width": 800, "height": 400 }): `
  aes(x: time, y: temp)
    | line()
    | point()
`
```
Supports `"type": "svg"` and `"type": "png"`.

## dispatch — Tag-based routing
```
|> dispatch
  case @env(production):
    |> jq: `{ mode: "prod" }`
  case @env(development):
    |> jq: `{ mode: "dev" }`
  default:
    |> jq: `{ mode: "unknown" }`
```

Supports boolean expressions in cases:
```
|> dispatch
  case @when(authenticated) and @when(admin):
    |> jq: `{ access: "admin_panel" }`
  case @when(authenticated):
    |> jq: `{ access: "dashboard" }`
  default:
    |> jq: `{ access: "login" }`
```

Guards can also be used as dispatch cases for data-driven branching:
```
|> dispatch
  case @guard(`.tier == "premium"`):
    |> jq: `{ message: "Premium tier", features: ["all"] }`
  case @guard(`.tier == "standard"`):
    |> jq: `{ message: "Standard tier", features: ["basic"] }`
  default:
    |> jq: `{ message: "Free tier", features: [] }`
```

## result — Status-based branching
```
|> result
  ok(200):
    |> jq: `{ success: true }`
  validationError(400):
    |> jq: `{ error: "Validation failed" }`
  authError(401):
    |> jq: `{ error: "Unauthorized" }`
  sqlError(500):
    |> jq: `{ error: "Database error" }`
  default(500):
    |> jq: `{ error: "Internal server error" }`
```

`result` routes execution based on the current `.errors` array:
- If `.errors` is missing or empty, `ok(...)` runs.
- Otherwise WebPipe matches `.errors[0].type` against the branch name, such as `validationError`, `authError`, or `sqlError`.
- If no branch matches, `default(...)` runs.
- The status code in parentheses becomes the HTTP status for that branch, and that branch's pipeline output becomes the new response.

## Middleware error types

`result` only branches on structured pipeline errors stored in `.errors`. Only some middlewares write those branchable error objects. Others abort the request with a top-level runtime/config failure instead.

Branchable `.errors` written into pipeline state:

- `auth` -> `authError { message }`
- `validate` -> `validationError { field, context, rule, message }`
- `pg` -> `sqlError { message, sqlstate?, severity?, query }`
- `fetch` -> `networkError { message, url? }`, `timeoutError { message }`, `httpError { status, message, url }`

Built-in middleware error behavior:

- `jq` -> no `.errors`; failures are usually top-level `middleware_execution_error`
- `auth` -> branchable `authError`; database/config failures can also abort with top-level `database_error` or `config_error`
- `validate` -> branchable `validationError`
- `pg` -> branchable `sqlError`; bad inline args can abort with top-level `middleware_execution_error`; missing DB or empty SQL can abort with top-level `database_error`
- `handlebars` -> no `.errors`; failures are usually top-level `middleware_execution_error`
- `fetch` -> branchable `networkError`, `timeoutError`, `httpError`; bad inline args can also abort with top-level `middleware_execution_error`
- `cache` -> no middleware-specific `.errors` during normal execution
- `lua` -> no `.errors`; failures are usually top-level `middleware_execution_error`
- `js` -> no `.errors`; failures are usually top-level `middleware_execution_error`
- `log` -> no middleware-specific `.errors` during normal execution
- `debug` -> no middleware-specific `.errors` during normal execution
- `join` -> no `.errors`; invalid config aborts with top-level `config_error`
- `graphql` -> no WebPipe `.errors`; invalid config or invalid inline variable args abort with top-level `config_error` or `middleware_execution_error`; GraphQL execution failures are returned in GraphQL response format `{ data, errors }`
- `rateLimit` -> no `.errors`; invalid config aborts with top-level `config_error`; exceeded limits abort with top-level `rate_limit_exceeded`
- `gg` -> no `.errors`; failures are usually top-level `middleware_execution_error`

If a middleware aborts with a top-level runtime/config error, `result` will not catch it. Use `result` only for `.errors` values already present in pipeline state.

Custom middleware output can also create your own branchable errors:
```
|> jq: `{
  errors: [{ type: "customError", message: "Something failed" }]
}`
|> result
  customError(400):
    |> jq: `{ error: .errors[0].message }`
```

## Conditional Execution Tags

Tags control when pipeline steps execute:

```
# Environment-specific
|> jq: `.mode = "debug"` @env(development)
|> cache: `ttl: 0` @!env(production)

# Feature flags
|> jq: `.beta = true` @flag(beta)

# Guards — JQ expression in backticks
|> pg: `DELETE FROM users WHERE id = $1` @guard(`.user.role == "admin"`)
|> jq: `. + { bonus: true }` @guard(`.user.credits > 50`)

# Runtime conditions (set by Lua with setWhen)
|> jq: `. + { metadata: true }` @when(add_metadata)

# Boolean expressions
|> jq: `. + { both: true }` @when(feature_a) and @when(feature_b)
|> jq: `. + { either: true }` @when(feature_a) or @when(feature_b)
|> jq: `. + { grouped: true }` (@when(a) or @when(b)) and @when(c)

# Multiple tags on a single step
|> fetch("https://api.example.com/admin") @result(adminData) @when(isAdmin)
```

## @result — Named results

Name the output of middleware steps for accumulation:

```
|> pg: `SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = $1` @result(user)
|> pg: `SELECT * FROM departments WHERE id = $1` @result(department)
|> jq: `{
  userName: .data.user.rows[0].name,
  deptName: .data.department.rows[0].name
}`
```

Named variables auto-name their results:
```
pg getUserQuery = `SELECT * FROM users`
|> pg: getUserQuery
# Result available at .data.getUserQuery
```

## Feature Flags

`featureFlags` is a special pipeline that runs before every route. Use it to set request-scoped flags once, then reference them later with `@flag(...)`, `$context.flags` in JQ, or `getFlag(...)` in Lua.

```
featureFlags =
  |> lua: `
    setFlag("experimental", true)
    setFlag("beta", (math.random() > 0.5))
    return {}
  `

GET /dashboard
  |> jq: `{ experimental: ($context.flags.experimental // false), beta: ($context.flags.beta // false) }`
  |> jq: `. + { betaEnabled: true }` @flag(beta)
```

## @when — Runtime conditions

Lua middleware can set transient conditions with `setWhen`:
```
|> lua: `
  setWhen("is_admin", true)
  setWhen("is_mobile", false)
  return request
`
|> dispatch
  case @when(is_admin):
    |> jq: `{ access: "admin" }`
  default:
    |> jq: `{ access: "user" }`
```

Read conditions back in Lua: `getWhen("is_admin")`. Access in JQ: `$context.conditions.is_admin`.

## Variables and Named Pipelines

```
jq myQuery = `{ greeting: "hello" }`
pg usersQuery = `SELECT * FROM users`
handlebars welcomeTemplate = `<h1>Welcome {{name}}</h1>`

pipeline withAuth =
  |> auth: "required"
  |> jq: `. + { authenticated: true }`

GET /protected
  |> pipeline: withAuth
  |> jq: `{ authenticated: .authenticated, user: .user }`
```

Pipelines can receive inline arguments:
```
pipeline getTeam =
  |> pg: `SELECT * FROM teams WHERE id = $1`

GET /team/:id
  |> pipeline({ sqlParams: [.params.id] }): getTeam
```

When you call a pipeline, its output is fed back into the parent using normal state semantics. If the helper returns an object, it merges into the current state. If it returns an array, scalar, or `null`, it replaces the current state.

## Imports

```
import "./lib/auth.wp" as auth

GET /login
  |> pipeline: auth::loginHandler
```

## Configuration

```
config pg {
  host: $WP_PG_HOST || "localhost"
  port: $WP_PG_PORT || "5432"
  database: $WP_PG_DATABASE || "mydb"
  user: $WP_PG_USER || "postgres"
  password: $WP_PG_PASSWORD || "password"
  ssl: false
  initialPoolSize: 10
  maxPoolSize: 20
}

config auth {
  sessionTtl: 604800
  cookieName: "wp_session"
  cookieSecure: false
  cookieHttpOnly: true
  cookieSameSite: "Lax"
  cookiePath: "/"
}

config cache { enabled: true, defaultTtl: 60 }
config log { enabled: true, level: "info" }
config graphql { endpoint: "/graphql" }
```

## GraphQL

```
graphqlSchema = `
  type User { id: ID!, name: String!, email: String! }
  type Query { users(limit: Int): [User!]! }
  type Mutation { createUser(name: String!, email: String!): User! }
`

query users =
  |> pg([.args.limit // .limit // 10]): `SELECT * FROM users LIMIT $1`
  |> jq: `.data.rows`

mutation createUser =
  |> pg([.args.name // .name, .args.email // .email]): `INSERT INTO users (name, email) VALUES ($1, $2) RETURNING *`
  |> jq: `.data.rows[0]`

resolver User.posts =
  |> pg([.parent.id]): `SELECT * FROM posts WHERE user_id = $1`
  |> jq: `.data.rows`
```

Resolver input shape:
- Root `query` and `mutation` pipelines receive GraphQL arguments both flattened at the top level, such as `.id` or `.limit`, and grouped under `.args`.
- Nested `resolver Type.field` pipelines also receive `.parent` for the parent object and `.context` for the caller's request/pipeline state.
- Prefer `.args.foo` in new code. The flattened `.foo` form is kept for backward compatibility.
- Example: `resolver User.posts` should usually read the parent object via `.parent.id`.

GraphQL middleware supports inline variables:
```
|> graphql({ userId: .targetId }): `
  query($userId: ID!) {
    user(id: $userId) { name email }
  }
`
```

GraphQL variables can also be stored and referenced:
```
graphql testMutation = `
  mutation($title: String!, $body: String!) {
    createPost(title: $title, body: $body) { id title }
  }
`
|> jq: `.graphqlParams = { title: .body.title, body: .body.body }`
|> graphql: testMutation
```

The GraphQL endpoint can be called directly via HTTP:
```
POST /graphql
  with body: { "query": "query { users { id name } }", "variables": {} }
```

### DataLoader — N+1 query prevention

For nested GraphQL resolvers that would otherwise cause N+1 queries, use the `loader` middleware with a batch pipeline. The loader automatically batches all parent keys and calls the pipeline once.

Define a loader pipeline that receives `{ keys: [...], args: {...}, context: {...} }`:
```
pipeline EmployeesByTeamLoader =
  |> pg([(.keys | map(tostring) | join(","))  , (.args.limit // 10)]): `
    SELECT id, name, email, team_id
    FROM (
      SELECT id, name, email, team_id,
        ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY team_id ORDER BY id) as rn
      FROM employees
      WHERE team_id::text = ANY(string_to_array($1, ','))
    ) ranked
    WHERE rn <= $2
  `
  |> jq: `
    reduce .data.rows[] as $row (
      {};
      .[$row.team_id | tostring] += [$row]
    )
  `
```

The loader pipeline must return a JSON object keyed by parent ID (e.g., `{ "1": [...], "2": [...] }`).

Wire it to a nested type resolver using `loader(.parent.id)`:
```
resolver Team.employees =
  |> loader(.parent.id): EmployeesByTeamLoader
```

`loader(...)` arguments work like this:
- The first argument is a JQ expression evaluated against each parent object. Those values are batched into `.keys`.
- The optional second argument is an object expression passed through as `.args`.

The `loader` middleware provides:
- `.keys` — batched values from the first loader argument (e.g., `[1, 2, 3]`)
- `.args` — the optional object from the second loader argument (e.g., `{ limit: 5 }`)
- `.context` — request context (headers, user, etc.)

Example with GraphQL field arguments:
```
resolver Team.employees =
  |> loader(.parent.id, { limit: .args.limit, offset: .args.offset }): EmployeesByTeamLoader
```

If the resolver is called for teams `1`, `2`, and `3` with `limit: 5`, the loader pipeline receives input like:
```
{ "keys": [1, 2, 3], "args": { "limit": 5 }, "context": { ... } }
```

Best practice for JQ-based loaders: capture `.keys` before any `reduce` or `map` that changes JQ's `.` context. Inside a `reduce`, `.` refers to the accumulator, so `.keys` will be `null` unless you save it first.

```
pipeline MyLoader =
  |> jq: `
    .keys as $keys |         # Capture keys before reduce
    reduce .items[] as $item (
      {};
      if ($keys | contains([$item.id])) then .[$item.id] = $item else . end
    )
  `
```

This turns N+1 queries into exactly 2 queries (one for the parent list, one batched for all children).

## Test DSL

Tests live in the same `.wp` file as routes:

Note: `describe` / `it` blocks use a declarative test DSL. They cannot contain pipeline steps such as `|> debug` or `|> middleware: ...`.

```
describe "feature name"
  # Describe-level variables are shared across all tests in this block
  let sharedVar = "shared across tests"
  let defaultRole = "user"
  let activeStatus = true

  with mock pg.usersQuery returning `{ "rows": [] }`

  it "does something"
    let userId = 123

    when calling GET /users/{{userId}}
    with headers `{ "x-api-key": "secret" }`
    and with body `{ "email": "test@example.com" }`
    and with cookies `{ "session_id": "abc123" }`
    then status is 200
    and status in 200..299
    and contentType is "application/json"
    and output equals `{ "success": true }`
    and output contains `{ "success": true }`
    and output matches `^<p>hello.*</p>$`
    and output `.name` equals "Alice"
    and output `.name` equals null
    and output `.message` contains "feature"
    and output `.items | length` equals 5
    and output `.data.teams | type` equals `"array"`
    and header "X-Request-ID" equals "req-123"
    and header "Set-Cookie" contains `session=alice_token`
    and selector `h1` exists
    and selector `#missing` does not exist
    and selector `h1.title` text equals "Welcome Home"
    and selector `.user-profile` text contains "Logged in as"
    and selector `ul.items > li` count equals 3
    and selector `ul.items > li` count is greater than 0
    and selector `a#login` attribute `href` equals "/login"
    and selector `a#login` attribute `href` contains "/login"
    and selector `a#login[href="/login"]` exists
    and selector `ul.items > li:nth-child(2)` text equals "Item 2"
```

### Let variables

Variables support strings, numbers, booleans, null, and backtick JSON:
```
let name = "Alice"
let count = 42
let active = true
let missing = null
let jsonData = `{"key": "value", "count": 10}`
```

Variables are interpolated with `{{varName}}` in paths, assertions, and string values:
```
it "uses variables"
  let userId = 42
  when calling GET /users/{{userId}}
  then output `.id` equals {{userId}}
  and output `.name` equals "User {{userId}}"
```

Test-level `let` overrides describe-level `let`:
```
describe "scoping"
  let role = "user"

  it "uses describe-level default"
    # role is "user" here

  it "overrides at test level"
    let role = "admin"
    # role is "admin" here
```

### JQ expressions in test data

Body, headers, cookies, input, and mock returning values all support JQ expressions. Let variables are accessible as `.varName` or `$varName`:

```
it "uses JQ in body"
  let firstName = "John"
  let lastName = "Doe"
  when calling POST /users
  with body `{
    fullName: (.firstName + " " + .lastName),
    tags: [$firstName, "user"],
    level: (if .score > 80 then "gold" else "silver" end)
  }`
  then status is 200

it "uses JQ in mocks"
  let userId = 42
  let userName = "Alice"
  when executing pipeline getUser
  with input `{ params: { id: .userId } }`
  and mock pg returning `{
    rows: [{
      id: .userId,
      name: .userName
    }]
  }`
  then output `.rows[0].id` equals {{userId}}
```

### Query strings in route calls

```
when calling GET /search?q=hello&limit=10
when calling GET /users/{{userId}}/posts?page={{page}}
```

### Executing pipelines and variables directly
```
it "tests a pipeline"
  when executing pipeline myPipeline
  with input `{ "params": { "id": "2" } }`
  then output equals `{ "rows": [...] }`

it "tests a variable"
  when executing variable pg myQuery
  with input `{ "sqlParams": [] }`
  then output `.rows | length` equals 3
```

### Mock targets

```
# Describe-level mocks
with mock query users returning `[{ "id": 1, "name": "Alice" }]`
and mock mutation createUser returning `{ "id": 99 }`
with mock pg.usersQuery returning `{ "rows": [] }`
with mock pg returning `{ "rows": [] }`
with mock pipeline myHelper returning `{ "result": true }`

# Test-level mocks (override describe-level)
it "with override"
  when executing pipeline myPipeline
  with input `{ ... }`
  and mock pg returning `{ "rows": [...] }`
  and mock pg.teamsQuery returning `{ "rows": [...] }`
  and mock pipeline processItem returning `{ "mocked": true }`
```

### Call assertions (spying)
```
and call query users with `{ "limit": 10 }`
and call mutation createUser with `{ "name": "Alice", "email": "alice@example.com" }`
and call pipeline processItem with `{ "item": "widget", "quantity": 5, "price": 9.99 }`
```

## Common Pitfalls for Agents

- Test boundaries: `it` blocks are for declarative test setup and assertions only. Do not place `|>` pipeline steps inside a test case.
- Loader scoping: in JQ loaders, capture `.keys` or other input fields into variables before `reduce` or similar expressions that change what `.` means.
- Pipeline call semantics are shape-dependent: object outputs from `|> pipeline: helper` merge into the caller's current state, while arrays, scalars, and `null` replace it.
- Mock data and static snippets: prefer `jq variableName = \`...\`` for reusable JSON snippets, then reference them with `|> jq: variableName`.

## Running

```bash
webpipe app.wp                         # Serve on 127.0.0.1:7770
webpipe app.wp --port 8080             # Custom port
webpipe app.wp --test                  # Run tests
webpipe app.wp --test --verbose        # Verbose tests
webpipe app.wp --inspect               # Debug mode
```

